  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Colophon on the Casting of Type
  author: Byeon Gyeryang
  language: eng
  text: 'The invention of cast type serves to print the multitude of books and transmit them through endless ages—truly an inexhaustible blessing. Yet the forms of the characters first cast were not without imperfection, and those who printed lamented that the work proceeded with difficulty. In the eleventh month of winter in the year Yongle Gengzi, our Prince, moved by deepest concern, commanded Minister Yi Cheon, Vice Director of Public Works, to newly cast type of exquisite precision. He appointed Minister Kim Ik-jeong, Commissioner of Petitions, and Minister Jeong Cho, Left Counselor, to oversee the work. After seven months of labor, the task was completed, and those who printed rejoiced at its ease. Now a single day''s printing could yield more than twenty sheets. Respectfully consider: our Great King Gongjong established this art before us, and our present Majesty has advanced it further, yet the refinement of method has grown ever more perfect. Thus no book remains unprinted, and no person remains unlearned. The flourishing of culture advances daily, and the prosperity of our realm shall grow ever brighter. How different this from the rulers of Han and Tang, who fixed their minds narrowly on financial administration and military preparations, counting these the primary concerns of state! This is as distant as heaven from earth. Truly, this is the boundless blessing of our Joseon for ten thousand generations.'
  footnotes:
    - 'Yongle Gengzi: 1420 CE, during the reign of King Sejong the Great of Joseon'
    - This colophon celebrates the improvement of Joseon's movable metal type system, which revolutionized printing and literacy in Korea
    - Great King Gongjong refers to King Taejong, Sejong's father, who initiated typographic reforms
